        "excerpt": "Now appoint a king for us to judge us like all the nations.",
        "body": "The elders' delegation and their request in 8:5 have the surface appearance of responsible civic leadership responding to institutional failure. They identify the problem accurately (Samuel is old; his sons are corrupt), they bring it to the right person (Samuel, the recognized prophetic authority), and they propose a solution that was not without precedent (Deuteronomy 17:14-20). But the phrase that defines the request's character is 'like all the nations' (*kegol haggoyim*).\n\nThis phrase is an alarm throughout the Deuteronomic tradition. Deuteronomy 17:14 anticipates Israel will want a king 'like all the nations around me' — and Moses' legislation accepts this while regulating it. But the phrase in context is not neutral. Israel's entire covenant identity was built on differentiation from the nations. Leviticus 18:3 prohibits Israel from doing 'what is done in the land of Egypt' or 'what is done in the land of Canaan.' Deuteronomy 7:6 declares Israel 'a people holy to the LORD your God... chosen out of all the peoples on the face of the earth.' The demand to be 'like all the nations' is a demand to erase the covenant distinction that defined Israel's existence.\n\nSamuel's distress (8:6) is therefore not merely the wounded pride of a man being told his leadership era is over. It is the distress of a prophet who hears, beneath the political request, a theological reversal. When he prays (*palal*, 8:6), he is not asking God what to do — he is bringing the burden of what he has heard into God's presence, in the manner of a faithful mediator. The verb *palal* in Samuel's usage is always intercessory and oriented toward divine consultation (1 Samuel 7:5; 12:19, 23). Samuel is not paralyzed; he is priestly.\n\nD. A. Carson's observation about idolatry is relevant here: idolatry is rarely the worship of something ugly; it is almost always the worship of something good — family, security, national identity — pursued through means that bypass the living God. Israel did not want chaos; they wanted order. They did not want defeat; they wanted military security. The desire was not wicked on its face. What was wicked was the source from which they sought to satisfy it: human institutional power modeled on the pagan nations, rather than covenant trust in the divine King."
